    en: "New York law requires every driver in an accident to stop, share their name and insurance information, and help anyone who is hurt. Leaving the scene is a crime — even when the driver was not at fault. The charge gets worse when someone is injured, and much worse when someone dies. Many people leave because they panic, have no insurance, or are afraid of a DWI. Leaving almost always makes things worse. A victim of a hit-and-run is usually covered by their own uninsured motorist insurance if the other driver is never found."
